---
// The homepage hero's scroll-scrubbed transformation: a scruffy puppy is groomed by the
// Fairy Tails fairy's wand as you scroll. Ported from the design handoff
// (`Luxury dog grooming animation/design_handoff_hero_animation/`) — read its README for the
// choreography spec. The handoff's coordinates, easing and timing windows are FINAL and are
// reproduced verbatim. The five deliberate divergences, and why:
//
// 1. COLOUR. The handoff was designed against the salon's OLD brand blue (#00AFF1 — the legacy
//    "K9 Centre" logo) on a #FFFFFF page. This site is "Countryside editorial" (global.css
//    @theme): cream paper, moss greens, honey accents, and NO blue anywhere. Every blue literal
//    is remapped onto honey. The remap also re-anchors LIGHTNESS: the blue set carried its
//    sparkle on two dark members (#00AFF1, #0090C8) that only work on white — against this
//    hero's bg-moss-900 band they are the weakest of the four. Minimum contrast rises
//    3.04 → 5.93. Corollary: honey-500/600/700 must never be used for sparkle here — on moss
//    they read as mud.
//
// 2. THE FAIRY IS PAINTED BY CSS. Her artwork's RGB is a flat blue gradient (hue locked
//    196–197°, S 100%, L 47%→30% top-to-bottom) — there is no modelling in it worth keeping,
//    only her alpha. Worse, that gradient runs light-at-head/dark-at-skirt: correct on white
//    (contrast grows downward 2.58→5.77), backwards on moss (4.74→2.12 — her skirt sinks into
//    the band), and no filter can invert a gradient's direction. So scripts/hero-assets.mjs
//    reduces her to an alpha stencil and CSS masks a honey gradient through it — chosen for
//    THIS background, tunable in one line, and preserving her translucent wing panes for free
//    (they live in her alpha). Same idiom as .paw-bullet in global.css.
//
// 3. NO JS LAYOUT. The handoff scales the stage by measuring the container in JS and writing px
//    width/height onto it (`measure()`). In the handoff that is safe — its script is inline and
//    synchronous — but Astro hoists component scripts to a DEFERRED type="module", so ported
//    as-is it would size the stage after first paint: layout shift on every load. Here the
//    whole static composition is percentages of an `aspect-ratio: 760/620` box, laid out and
//    scaled entirely by CSS: zero CLS, and no element is ever sized in px, so nothing can
//    overflow a narrow viewport. Only the PARTICLES — which exist solely because JS is running
//    — live in `.ft-fx`, a 760×620 layer scaled by a JS-set `--ft-s` (from the CONTAINER's
//    width, never innerWidth) that defaults to scale(0) so they cannot flash at 1:1.
//
// 4. AUTHORED FINISHED, ARMED BACKWARDS. The markup below renders the FINAL state — groomed
//    dog, fairy present, bow on. The p=0 "before" state is imposed by CSS, only under
//    [data-ft-armed] and only inside @media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference). This is
//    the inverse of the handoff (which bakes p=0 into its HTML) and it buys two of the brief's
//    hard requirements for free: with JS off the hero is a correct finished illustration rather
//    than a dull grey dog with no fairy, and reduced-motion users get the finished state with
//    no flash rather than a p=0 paint that snaps forward. See the arming script for the rest.
//
// 5. TWO MODES, ONE TIMELINE. Desktop (≥lg) scrubs to a sticky 240vh track, per the handoff
//    (whose 340vh is a documented tuning knob) — the CTA stays pinned on screen throughout.
//    Below lg there is NO scroll-jack: the stage plays through once when it scrolls into view.
//    Owner rule (CLAUDE.md): most of this salon's customers arrive on a phone, and pinning them
//    for 3.4 screens before any content is a conversion cost the animation has not earned.
//    Only the PRODUCER of p forks; update(p) is one pure function, not two code paths.
import { getImage } from 'astro:assets';
import dogSrc from '../assets/pages/home/hero-dog.png';
import fairyStencil from '../assets/pages/home/hero-fairy-stencil.png';

// ONE derivative, at the source's NATIVE width, with NO widths/densities — so the <img> and the
// sheen's CSS mask resolve to the same deterministic URL and the browser fetches the dog ONCE.
// (Any srcset would emit several candidate URLs; the mask can only name one, so it would very
// likely name the one the browser didn't pick and pay for a second download.) 664KB → 41KB.
// 635px covers every slot we render: ~300 CSS px at desktop and ~177 on a phone, i.e. 2–3x.
//
// Native width is not laziness — it is the SMALLEST option, counter-intuitively. Measured, at
// q80: 635w (native) 52.9KB · 560w 63.9KB · 500w 54.9KB. Any downscale resamples smooth painted
// fur into ringing artefacts that cost more entropy than the pixels saved. Do not "optimise"
// this by shrinking it.
//
// q68 vs Astro's default q80 saves 12KB (52.9 → 40.7) and was compared side by side at 2x — on
// a soft-gradient illustration like this it is indistinguishable, with no banding in the fur or
// around the eyes. q60 is also clean if bytes ever get desperate.
const dog = await getImage({ src: dogSrc, format: 'webp', width: 635, quality: 68 });

// The fairy's mask, also at native width and for the same reason (downscaling a hard-edged
// two-tone stencil ADDS antialiasing entropy: 440w webp 8.4KB · 360w 19.3KB · 300w 15.5KB).
// webp beats her PNG here (8.4KB vs 12.8KB) because hero-assets.mjs flattens her RGB to a
// constant, leaving only the alpha channel to encode. Verified to decode as a mask in WebKit —
// see scripts/hero-mask-support.mjs, which exists because a mask that fails to load falls back
// to `none`, and an unmasked fairy is a solid gold RECTANGLE in the hero.
const fairy = await getImage({ src: fairyStencil, format: 'webp', width: 440 });

// Stage coordinates from the handoff live in a 760×620 space; percentages keep that exact
// composition while letting CSS do the scaling. Kept as literal maths so the handoff's numbers
// stay greppable against its README.
const SW = 760;
const SH = 620;
const pct = (n: number, of: number) => `${((n / of) * 100).toFixed(4)}%`;
---

<div class="ft-stage" data-hero-stage aria-hidden="true">
  {/* Grounding. The handoff uses rgba(28,28,30,.05) — on moss-900 that composites to under
      1.5/255 per channel, i.e. mathematically invisible, and she would float. Replaced by the
      pair a dark band actually needs: a warm pool (the fairy's light falling on the floor) and
      a contact core DARKER than the band, which is the only thing that reads as contact here.
      Both warm up as the groom completes. */}
  <div class="ft-ground-pool"></div>
  <div class="ft-ground-core"></div>

  {/* Ambient motes — the only time-based (non-scroll) motion in the piece. Alphas are lifted
      ~+0.06 over the handoff's: at 5–8px under blur(1px), its values composite to roughly
      (102,97,62) over moss — present, but too timid to register. */}
  <div class="ft-mote ft-mote-1"></div>
  <div class="ft-mote ft-mote-2"></div>
  <div class="ft-mote ft-mote-3"></div>

  {/* Dog: muted "before" underneath, full-colour "after" on top behind a soft reveal mask.
      Plain <img>, not <Image>: we need the single shared URL (see the getImage note above), and
      width/height are set so the box is reserved before the bytes arrive.

      loading="lazy" is deliberate and does the right thing on BOTH layouts, because lazy only
      defers images that are OUT of the viewport: on desktop the stage is beside the headline, so
      it loads at once; on a phone it sits below the fold, so it waits. That matters more than it
      sounds. The LCP element here is the H1, which cannot paint until Fraunces arrives — and an
      eager, fetchpriority="high" dog (measured: it cost ~0.3s of LCP) queues 54KB of decoration
      AHEAD of the font the headline is waiting on. The illustration must never outrank the
      headline; nothing about it is worth a slower first impression. */}
  <div class="ft-dog" data-dog>
    <img
      class="ft-dog-img ft-dog-before"
      src={dog.src}
      width={dog.attributes.width}
      height={dog.attributes.height}
      alt=""
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      fetchpriority="low"
      data-before
    />
    <div class="ft-after" data-after>
      <img
        class="ft-dog-img"
        src={dog.src}
        width={dog.attributes.width}
        height={dog.attributes.height}
        alt=""
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
        fetchpriority="low"
      />
      {/* The mask URL must be interpolated into an INLINE STYLE attribute, never written as a
          literal url() in the <style> block below: a scoped block is compiled statically, so it
          cannot see this runtime value, and a literal path there would be resolved by Vite
          against the wrong thing — silently 404ing with no build warning and no gate to catch
          it. This is the one hazard in the whole component that nothing downstream would flag. */}
      <div class="ft-sheen-clip" style={`--ft-dog-mask: url('${dog.src}')`}>
        <div class="ft-sheen" data-sheen></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    {/* Bow — the sequence's payoff, popping onto the topknot at p≈.735.
        COLOUR: the handoff paints it brand blue. Honey (the obvious accent) was measured and
        rejected — the topknot it lands on is #f8e1bb–#eebc7b, which IS honey-300 territory, so a
        honey bow is invisible on it. Moss is the only palette hue separating from her coat on
        both hue and lightness (3.2:1 against the topknot), it echoes the band, and the honey
        knot lands a focal glint exactly at the pop.
        SHAPE: redrawn, and this one is not a taste call. The handoff's loops sweep UPWARD from
        the knot and its tails hang below — at the size this actually renders (33px desktop /
        47px tablet) that silhouette is a MOTH, and with its big round knot it read as a green
        flower. Rendered at 1:1 against the topknot's real colour to check, which is the only way
        to judge a 33px mark. A bow's loops sit HORIZONTAL, level with the knot; that reads
        instantly at 33px. Tails were dropped for the same reason — at this size they are two
        dark specks under the knot, which is exactly what made it look insectile. */}
    <svg class="ft-bow" data-bow viewBox="0 0 44 34" width="44" height="34">
      <path
        d="M21.2 17 C15 12 8 8.6 4.6 9.4 C2.2 10.2 2.2 23.8 4.6 24.6 C8 25.4 15 22 21.2 17 Z"
        fill="#596f44"></path>
      <path
        d="M22.8 17 C29 12 36 8.6 39.4 9.4 C41.8 10.2 41.8 23.8 39.4 24.6 C36 25.4 29 22 22.8 17 Z"
        fill="#596f44"></path>
      <rect x="19.8" y="12.4" width="4.4" height="9.2" rx="2.2" fill="#dfa854"></rect>
    </svg>
  </div>

  {/* Fairy — static by explicit client request (no path movement); she only fades and settles.
      The glow lives on this wrapper, NOT on .ft-fairy-art: CSS applies filter BEFORE mask, so a
      drop-shadow on the masked element would be a shadow of its rectangular box which its own
      mask then clips away. On the parent it correctly traces her silhouette. */}
  <div class="ft-fairy" data-fairy>
    <div class="ft-fairy-art" style={`--ft-fairy-mask: url('${fairy.src}')`}></div>
    <svg class="ft-wand-star" viewBox="-6 -6 12 12" width="22" height="22">
      <path
        d="M0 -5 C0.9 -1.6 1.6 -0.9 5 0 C1.6 0.9 0.9 1.6 0 5 C-0.9 1.6 -1.6 0.9 -5 0 C-1.6 -0.9 -0.9 -1.6 0 -5 Z"
        fill="#fbf7ed"></path>
    </svg>
  </div>

  {/* Particle layer — populated by JS only. scale(0) until measured, so nothing can flash. */}
  <div class="ft-fx" data-fx></div>
</div>

<script is:inline>
  // Arms the stage to its p=0 "before" state BEFORE first paint. The markup is authored at the
  // FINISHED state (see divergence 4), and the module script that drives the animation is
  // deferred — so without this, every load would paint the groomed dog and then snap backwards.
  //
  // The safety net matters as much as the arming: if the module never initialises (bundle
  // failed, threw, browser too old), disarm and let the finished illustration stand. The brief
  // requires the hero stay usable when the animation does not load, and a permanently dull dog
  // with no fairy is not that. JS off entirely → this never runs → finished state → also right.
  (function () {
    var s = document.querySelector('[data-hero-stage]');
    if (!s) return;
    s.setAttribute('data-ft-armed', '');
    setTimeout(function () {
      if (!s.dataset.ftInit) s.removeAttribute('data-ft-armed');
    }, 3000);
  })();
</script>

<style
  define:vars={{
    dogL: pct(202, SW),
    dogT: pct(150, SH),
    dogW: pct(376, SW),
    dogH: pct(440, SH),
    fairyL: pct(572, SW),
    fairyT: pct(64, SH),
    fairyW: pct(180, SW),
    fairyH: pct(236, SH),
    bowL: pct(168, 376),
    bowT: pct(57, 440),
    bowW: pct(46, 376),
    bowH: pct(36, 440),
  }}
>
  /* The stage is a pure-CSS box: aspect-ratio reserves it before JS, and every child is a
     percentage of it, so the composition scales to any width with no measuring and no shift. */
  .ft-stage {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 760 / 620;
    /* The stage never eats a tap, a scroll or a drag — the brief's hard rule that no
       interaction may interfere with scrolling, navigation or buttons. */
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  /* Both grounds sit at the paws' contact line (stage y≈572) — 8px above the handoff's ellipse,
     because hero-assets.mjs cut the artwork's painted floor away at source y≈714, and the
     handoff's y580 was aligned to that floor rather than to her paws. */
  .ft-ground-pool,
  .ft-ground-core {
    position: absolute;
    left: 50%;
    translate: -50% 0;
    border-radius: 50%;
    /* The room warms as she is groomed. Default 1 = finished; armed resets it to 0. */
    opacity: calc(0.5 + 0.5 * var(--ft-warm, 1));
  }
  .ft-ground-pool {
    top: 88.7097%;
    width: 54%;
    height: 7.0968%;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse at center,
      rgb(236 194 124 / 0.26) 0%,
      rgb(236 194 124 / 0.09) 54%,
      rgb(236 194 124 / 0) 78%
    );
    filter: blur(6px);
  }
  .ft-ground-core {
    top: 91.6129%;
    width: 38%;
    height: 2.9032%;
    background: radial-gradient(ellipse at center, rgb(18 26 18 / 0.5) 0%, rgb(18 26 18 / 0) 72%);
    filter: blur(5px);
  }

  .ft-mote {
    position: absolute;
    aspect-ratio: 1;
    border-radius: 50%;
    filter: blur(1px);
    animation: ftFloat 6s ease-in-out infinite alternate;
  }
  .ft-mote-1 {
    left: 15.7895%;
    top: 19.3548%;
    width: 1.0526%;
    background: rgb(243 220 174 / 0.42);
  }
  .ft-mote-2 {
    left: 92.1053%;
    top: 54.8387%;
    width: 0.7895%;
    background: rgb(236 194 124 / 0.34);
    animation-duration: 7.5s;
    animation-delay: 0.8s;
  }
  .ft-mote-3 {
    left: 11.8421%;
    top: 69.3548%;
    width: 0.6579%;
    background: rgb(236 194 124 / 0.26);
    animation-duration: 5.2s;
    animation-delay: 1.6s;
  }
  @keyframes ftFloat {
    0% {
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
    100% {
      transform: translateY(-14px);
    }
  }

  .ft-dog {
    position: absolute;
    left: var(--dogL);
    top: var(--dogT);
    width: var(--dogW);
    height: var(--dogH);
    z-index: 3;
    will-change: transform;
    /* FINISHED state = the proud lift, held. Must match update(1) exactly, or JS-off and
       reduced-motion render a dog 6px lower than the animation's own end state. */
    transform: translateY(-6px);
  }
  .ft-dog-img {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
  }
  /* FINISHED state: the muted layer is gone and the after-layer is fully revealed. */
  .ft-dog-before {
    opacity: 0;
    /* The handoff's saturate(.4) brightness(.94) was tuned against a WHITE page, where merely
       draining the colour is enough to read as dull. On a dark band a desaturated warm dog
       still reads as lit and healthy, so the brightness drop is deepened until she genuinely
       looks unkempt — but kept warm rather than grey: a scruffy dog is dusty, not monochrome. */
    filter: saturate(0.34) brightness(0.72) contrast(0.94);
  }
  .ft-after {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
  }
  .ft-sheen-clip {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    /* Hand-prefixed: this repo has no autoprefixer (postcss.config.mjs loads only
       @tailwindcss/postcss), matching global.css's .paw-bullet. */
    -webkit-mask-image: var(--ft-dog-mask);
    -webkit-mask-size: 100% 100%;
    -webkit-mask-repeat: no-repeat;
    mask-image: var(--ft-dog-mask);
    mask-size: 100% 100%;
    mask-repeat: no-repeat;
  }
  .ft-sheen {
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: -20%;
    width: 30%;
    height: 140%;
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateX(-120%);
    background: linear-gradient(
      102deg,
      rgb(251 247 237 / 0) 0%,
      rgb(251 247 237 / 0.32) 50%,
      rgb(251 247 237 / 0) 100%
    );
  }

  .ft-bow {
    position: absolute;
    left: var(--bowL);
    top: var(--bowT);
    width: var(--bowW);
    height: var(--bowH);
    transform-origin: 50% 50%;
    z-index: 4;
  }

  .ft-fairy {
    position: absolute;
    left: var(--fairyL);
    top: var(--fairyT);
    width: var(--fairyW);
    height: var(--fairyH);
    z-index: 6;
    transform-origin: 50% 60%;
    /* On a dark band a drop shadow only muddies her; she is the light SOURCE the scene is lit
       by, so she glows instead. Must live here, not on .ft-fairy-art — see the markup note. */
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 16px rgb(236 194 124 / 0.3));
  }
  .ft-fairy-art {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    -webkit-mask: var(--ft-fairy-mask) 0 0 / 100% 100% no-repeat;
    mask: var(--ft-fairy-mask) 0 0 / 100% 100% no-repeat;
    /* Her colour, in one line. Runs light-at-head → gold-at-hem: it keeps the artwork's
       light-from-above reading, but compressed so the darkest stop still holds 4.5:1 against
       the band instead of the original's 2.12. */
    background: linear-gradient(180deg, #f3dcae 0%, #ecc27c 38%, #dfa854 72%, #cf9038 100%);
  }
  .ft-wand-star {
    position: absolute;
    /* Centred on the wand tip = stage (583,158) = fairy-relative (11, 94), so the shower's
       emission origin and the visible star are the same point and the stars read as coming out
       of the wand. (The handoff parks this star at wrapper (18,126) — mid-skirt, nowhere near
       her wand — which reads as a stray dot. Moved deliberately.) */
    left: 6.1111%;
    top: 39.8305%;
    width: 12.2222%;
    height: auto;
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  }

  .ft-fx {
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
    width: 760px;
    height: 620px;
    z-index: 5;
    transform-origin: top left;
    /* scale(0) until JS measures: particles must never flash at 1:1 on a small stage. */
    transform: scale(var(--ft-s, 0));
  }

  /* ── The p=0 "before" state ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Imposed only when JS has armed the stage AND the visitor accepts motion. Everything the
     animation drives must have its start value here, or it will pop on the first frame. */
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference) {
    [data-ft-armed] {
      --ft-warm: 0;
    }
    [data-ft-armed] .ft-dog-before {
      opacity: 1;
    }
    [data-ft-armed] .ft-dog {
      transform: none; /* she has not earned the lift yet */
    }
    [data-ft-armed] .ft-after {
      -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(90deg, transparent 100%, #000 118%);
      mask-image: linear-gradient(90deg, transparent 100%, #000 118%);
    }
    [data-ft-armed] .ft-bow {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: scale(0.3);
    }
    [data-ft-armed] .ft-fairy {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: scale(0.96);
    }
  }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .ft-mote {
      animation: none;
    }
  }
</style>

<script>
  // Drives the stage. One pure update(p); only the PRODUCER of p forks by viewport.
  //
  // ⚠️ Astro dedupes component scripts: this module runs at most ONCE per session, even across
  // client-side navigations (ClientRouter). Two consequences shape everything below:
  //   · Document-scoped listeners are registered HERE, at module scope — never inside init(),
  //     where they would accumulate one per navigation (the stage element is recreated on every
  //     swap; nothing in src/ uses transition:persist).
  //   · init() must re-run per page via astro:page-load, or navigating back to / would leave a
  //     fresh, never-initialised stage: permanently dull, unscrubbed, un-armed. The failure mode
  //     of getting this wrong is NOT double-init — the dedupe makes that impossible — it is
  //     nothing running at all.
  const STAR =
    'M0 -5 C0.9 -1.6 1.6 -0.9 5 0 C1.6 0.9 0.9 1.6 0 5 C-0.9 1.6 -1.6 0.9 -5 0 C-1.6 -0.9 -0.9 -1.6 0 -5 Z';

  // ── Tuning knobs (the handoff names track length and dust count as the intended two; the
  // mobile playthrough's duration is the third, and is ours). ────────────────────────────────
  const N_DUST = 34;
  const PLAY_MS = 3400;

  // The honey remap of the handoff's blue palette — see divergence 1 in the frontmatter.
  const DUST_COLORS = ['#ecc27c', '#f3dcae', '#dfa854', '#fbf7ed'];

  // Stage constants (760×620 space) — verbatim from the handoff.
  const TIP = [583, 158];
  const DOG_L = 202;
  const DOG_W = 376;
  const CONTOUR: [number, number][] = [
    [548, 335],
    [503, 247],
    [450, 194],
    [398, 163],
    [352, 190],
    [307, 238],
    [262, 326],
    [240, 423],
  ];

  const S = (p: number, a: number, b: number) => Math.min(1, Math.max(0, (p - a) / (b - a)));
  const eio = (t: number) => (t < 0.5 ? 4 * t * t * t : 1 - Math.pow(-2 * t + 2, 3) / 2);
  const eo = (t: number) => 1 - Math.pow(1 - t, 3);
  const eioInv = (v: number) =>
    v <= 0 ? 0 : v >= 1 ? 1 : v < 0.5 ? Math.cbrt(v / 4) : 1 - Math.cbrt(2 * (1 - v)) / 2;
  const front = (p: number) => 640 - 535 * eio(S(p, 0.14, 0.7));

  function contourY(x: number) {
    if (x >= CONTOUR[0][0]) return CONTOUR[0][1];
    for (let i = 0; i < CONTOUR.length - 1; i++) {
      const a = CONTOUR[i];
      const b = CONTOUR[i + 1];
      if (x <= a[0] && x >= b[0]) return a[1] + ((b[1] - a[1]) * (a[0] - x)) / (a[0] - b[0] || 1);
    }
    return CONTOUR[CONTOUR.length - 1][1];
  }

  let teardown: (() => void) | null = null;

  function initHeroStage() {
    const stage = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-hero-stage]');
    const track = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-hero-track]');
    if (!stage || !track || stage.dataset.ftInit) return;
    stage.dataset.ftInit = '1';

    const q = <T extends Element>(s: string) => stage.querySelector<T>(s);
    const fx = q<HTMLElement>('[data-fx]')!;
    const elDog = q<HTMLElement>('[data-dog]')!;
    const elBefore = q<HTMLElement>('[data-before]')!;
    const elAfter = q<HTMLElement>('[data-after]')!;
    const elSheen = q<HTMLElement>('[data-sheen]')!;
    const elBow = q<HTMLElement>('[data-bow]')!;
    const elFairy = q<HTMLElement>('[data-fairy]')!;
    const elCue = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-hero-cue]');

    // ── Particles. One fragment, one reflow. No will-change: 49 permanently-promoted
    // compositor layers costs more in raster memory on a mid-range phone than it saves. ──────
    const frag = document.createDocumentFragment();
    const mkStar = (size: number, color: string, glow: boolean) => {
      const d = document.createElement('div');
      d.style.cssText = 'position:absolute;left:0;top:0;opacity:0';
      d.innerHTML =
        `<svg width="${size}" height="${size}" viewBox="-6 -6 12 12"` +
        (glow ? ' style="filter:drop-shadow(0 0 4px rgba(243,220,174,.75))"' : '') +
        `><path d="${STAR}" fill="${color}"></path></svg>`;
      frag.appendChild(d);
      return d;
    };

    const dust = Array.from({ length: N_DUST }, (_, i) => {
      const s = (i * 0.618034) % 1;
      const s2 = (i * 0.377) % 1;
      return {
        el: mkStar(10 + Math.round(s2 * 9), DUST_COLORS[i % 4], true),
        t: 0.1 + (i / (N_DUST - 1)) * 0.52 + (s - 0.5) * 0.02,
        dx: (s2 - 0.5) * 44,
        dy: -10 + s * 26,
        arc: s2 * 46,
        rot: s * 360,
      };
    });

    const glints = [...CONTOUR, [255, 511] as [number, number]].map((pt, i) => {
      const v = Math.min(1, Math.max(0, (640 - pt[0]) / 535));
      const el = mkStar(i % 2 ? 19 : 26, i % 3 === 2 ? '#fbf7ed' : '#f3dcae', false);
      el.style.left = `${pt[0]}px`;
      el.style.top = `${pt[1] - 14}px`;
      return { el, t: 0.14 + 0.56 * eioInv(v) };
    });

    // The burst rides the bow, so it must carry the dog's proud lift itself: it lives in the fx
    // layer (which does not lift) while the bow is inside .ft-dog (which does).
    //
    // Sized UP from the handoff's 13 units / 8→46px radius, and this is a port correction rather
    // than a taste change. The handoff scales its stage to `min(innerWidth*.92, 760)/760`, i.e.
    // it is authored for s=1 — a 760px stage. Inside this hero's two-column grid the stage is
    // ~590px, so every value lands at ~78%: the burst measured 7px stars radiating 29px, which
    // put them INSIDE her topknot fur rather than clear of it. Invisible, on the frame that is
    // supposed to be the payoff. Bigger stars and a radius that clears the tuft restore the
    // handoff's intent at this stage's actual size.
    const burst = Array.from({ length: 6 }, (_, i) => {
      const el = mkStar(18, i % 2 ? '#fbf7ed' : '#ecc27c', true);
      el.style.left = `${DOG_L + 185}px`;
      el.style.top = `${150 + 67}px`;
      return { el, ang: (i / 6) * Math.PI * 2 - 0.5 };
    });
    fx.appendChild(frag);

    // ── The whole animation: one pure function of p ───────────────────────────────────────
    function update(p: number) {
      const frontX = front(p);
      const fo = S(p, 0.04, 0.1);
      elFairy.style.opacity = String(fo);
      elFairy.style.transform = `scale(${0.96 + 0.04 * eo(fo)})`;

      const e = (frontX - DOG_L) / (DOG_W / 100);
      const g = `linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(0,0,0,0) ${e - 9}%, #000 ${e + 9}%)`;
      elAfter.style.setProperty('-webkit-mask-image', g);
      elAfter.style.setProperty('mask-image', g);
      elBefore.style.opacity = String(1 - S(p, 0.66, 0.73));

      // The room warms as she is revealed.
      stage.style.setProperty('--ft-warm', String(eio(S(p, 0.14, 0.7))));

      const lift = -6 * eo(S(p, 0.74, 0.84));
      elDog.style.transform = `translateY(${lift}px)`;

      const sp = S(p, 0.78, 0.93);
      elSheen.style.transform = `translateX(${-120 + 480 * eio(sp)}%)`;
      elSheen.style.opacity = sp > 0 && sp < 1 ? '1' : '0';

      const po = S(p, 0.735, 0.8);
      const sc = po <= 0 ? 0.3 : po < 0.75 ? 0.3 + 0.76 * eo(po / 0.75) : 1.06 - 0.06 * ((po - 0.75) / 0.25);
      elBow.style.transform = `scale(${sc}) rotate(${-6 + 6 * po}deg)`;
      elBow.style.opacity = String(Math.min(1, po * 4));

      const bp = S(p, 0.75, 0.86);
      for (const b of burst) {
        const d = 12 + 56 * eo(bp); // handoff 8→46: widened to clear the topknot — see the note above
        b.el.style.transform = `translate(${Math.cos(b.ang) * d}px,${Math.sin(b.ang) * d + lift}px) scale(${0.45 + 0.55 * bp})`;
        b.el.style.opacity = bp <= 0 || bp >= 1 ? '0' : String(Math.sin(bp * Math.PI) * 0.9);
      }

      for (const s of glints) {
        const lo = S(p, s.t - 0.035, s.t + 0.05);
        s.el.style.transform = `translate(-50%,-50%) scale(${0.4 + 0.8 * eo(lo)}) rotate(${lo * 90}deg)`;
        s.el.style.opacity = lo <= 0 || lo >= 1 ? '0' : String(Math.sin(lo * Math.PI));
      }

      for (const d of dust) {
        const a = (p - d.t) / 0.11;
        if (a <= 0 || a >= 1) {
          d.el.style.opacity = '0';
          continue;
        }
        const lx = Math.min(566, front(d.t + 0.06)) + d.dx;
        const ly = contourY(lx) + d.dy;
        const cx = (TIP[0] + lx) / 2;
        const cy = Math.min(TIP[1], ly) - 60 - d.arc;
        const u = 1 - a;
        const x = u * u * TIP[0] + 2 * u * a * cx + a * a * lx;
        const y = u * u * TIP[1] + 2 * u * a * cy + a * a * ly;
        d.el.style.transform = `translate(${x}px,${y}px) scale(${0.5 + 0.6 * a}) rotate(${d.rot + a * 60}deg)`;
        d.el.style.opacity = String(Math.min(1, a * 5) * (a > 0.8 ? (1 - a) / 0.2 : 1) * 0.95);
      }

      if (elCue) elCue.style.opacity = String(1 - S(p, 0.02, 0.07));
    }

    // ── Scale the particle layer from the CONTAINER's width — never innerWidth. A stage that
    // renders unscaled at 760px is the one way this component can overflow a phone. ──────────
    const ro = new ResizeObserver(([entry]) => {
      const w = entry.contentRect.width;
      if (!w) return; // zero-width (display:none ancestor) would set scale(0) and hide it silently
      fx.style.setProperty('--ft-s', String(w / 760));
    });
    ro.observe(stage);

    // ── Producers of p ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    const mqDesktop = matchMedia('(min-width: 64rem)'); // rem, to track Tailwind's lg exactly
    const mqReduce = matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)');

    let p = 0;
    let rendered = -1;
    let raf = 0;
    let playT0 = 0;
    let played = false;
    let visible = false;
    // Has the STAGE itself actually been seen? Distinct from `visible`, which tracks the TRACK
    // (with a 200px head start) purely to decide whether the loop is worth running. Conflating
    // the two is a real bug, not a theoretical one — see the armer below.
    let playArmed = false;
    let mode: 'scroll' | 'play' | 'static' = 'static';

    const render = (v: number) => {
      if (v === rendered) return; // parked at a stable p: skip the writes, keep the loop cheap
      rendered = v;
      update(v);
    };

    function scrollTarget() {
      const r = track.getBoundingClientRect();
      const span = r.height - innerHeight;
      return span > 10 ? Math.min(1, Math.max(0, -r.top / span)) : r.top < 0 ? 1 : 0;
    }

    function frame(now: number) {
      raf = 0;
      if (mode === 'scroll') {
        const t = scrollTarget();
        const d = t - p;
        p = Math.abs(d) < 0.0005 ? t : p + d * 0.16; // damped approach = the engineered scrub feel
        render(p);
        if (visible) raf = requestAnimationFrame(frame);
      } else if (mode === 'play') {
        p = Math.min(1, (now - playT0) / PLAY_MS);
        render(p);
        if (p >= 1) played = true;
        else if (visible) raf = requestAnimationFrame(frame);
      }
    }

    const start = () => {
      if (raf || mode === 'static') return;
      // In play mode the clock must not tick until the stage has actually been seen.
      if (mode === 'play' && !playArmed && !played) return;
      raf = requestAnimationFrame(frame);
    };
    const stop = () => {
      if (raf) cancelAnimationFrame(raf);
      raf = 0;
    };

    function applyMode() {
      stop();
      if (mqReduce.matches) {
        // Not "less motion" but a different render path: the finished state, no loop, no
        // particles moving. The CSS arming is already inert under this media query, so the
        // markup is correct on its own — update(1) only pins it against a live mode switch.
        mode = 'static';
        p = 1;
        render(1);
        return;
      }
      if (mqDesktop.matches) {
        mode = 'scroll';
        p = scrollTarget(); // snap, don't damp: new geometry, same tick, no lurch
        render(p);
      } else {
        mode = 'play';
        if (played || p >= 1) {
          p = 1;
          render(1);
          return; // never replay on a rotation
        }
        // A scrub abandoned mid-way continues by time from exactly where it stopped — but only
        // once the stage has been seen. Seeding the clock before that is what burns it unseen.
        if (playArmed) playT0 = performance.now() - p * PLAY_MS;
      }
      if (visible) start();
    }

    // Off-screen the loop is pure battery burn. rootMargin gives it a head start so it is
    // already settled by the time the stage is on screen.
    const io = new IntersectionObserver(
      ([entry]) => {
        visible = entry.isIntersecting;
        if (visible) {
          if (mode === 'play' && !played && playArmed) playT0 = performance.now() - p * PLAY_MS;
          start();
        } else {
          stop();
          // Snap to where the scroll says we are. Without this, flicking past the track leaves
          // the hero frozen half-groomed for the rest of the session.
          if (mode === 'scroll') {
            p = scrollTarget();
            render(p);
          }
        }
      },
      { rootMargin: '200px 0px' },
    );
    io.observe(track);

    // Arms the play-once clock, and it MUST watch the stage rather than the track.
    //
    // Below lg the `lg:h-[240vh]` collapses, so the track IS the whole hero — it starts at the
    // top of the document and is therefore already intersecting at scrollY=0, 200px head start
    // or not. Seeding the clock from that observer meant the 3.4s playthrough ran to completion
    // while the stage was ~5% visible below the fold, latched `played`, and left every phone
    // visitor arriving at a static, already-finished dog. The animation never played at all —
    // the exact opposite of the mobile design. (Widening the rootMargin or simply re-pointing
    // the existing observer at the stage does NOT fix it: the stage sits ~653px down, inside
    // vh+200 on every common phone. It needs its own observer with a real threshold.)
    const ioPlay = new IntersectionObserver(
      ([entry]) => {
        if (!entry.isIntersecting || playArmed) return;
        playArmed = true;
        ioPlay.disconnect(); // one-shot: it only ever needs to answer "has she been seen?"
        if (mode === 'play' && !played) {
          playT0 = performance.now() - p * PLAY_MS;
          start();
        }
      },
      { threshold: 0.35 },
    );
    ioPlay.observe(stage);

    // Live, not read-once: every other motion check in this repo responds to the OS setting
    // changing, and this one flips a whole render path.
    mqReduce.addEventListener('change', applyMode);
    mqDesktop.addEventListener('change', applyMode);
    applyMode();

    teardown = () => {
      stop();
      io.disconnect();
      ioPlay.disconnect();
      ro.disconnect();
      mqReduce.removeEventListener('change', applyMode);
      mqDesktop.removeEventListener('change', applyMode);
      delete stage.dataset.ftInit;
    };
  }

  initHeroStage();
  document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initHeroStage);
  document.addEventListener('astro:before-swap', (e) => {
    teardown?.();
    teardown = null;
    // Arm the INCOMING document before it paints. The is:inline arming script above cannot help
    // here: Astro runs scripts after the swap has already been painted, and it is deduped to
    // once per session anyway — so on a client-side nav back to /, this is the only thing
    // standing between the visitor and a finished-then-snap-backwards flash.
    (e as any).newDocument?.querySelector('[data-hero-stage]')?.setAttribute('data-ft-armed', '');
  });
</script>
